            />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="section pt-0">
      <div class="max-w-[1200px] mx-auto">
        <div class="mt-10">
          <div class="mb-10 items-center mt-20 space-y-10">
            <div>
              <p>
                As more Nigerians embrace solar energy, understanding how much electricity your solar panels are producing becomes essential. Solar power is a
                sustainable solution to Nigeria's erratic power supply, but to truly benefit from your system, you need to monitor its performance. Here's a
                simple guide on how to calculate the electricity your solar panels generate, ensuring you get the most out of your investment.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h1 class="text-2xl font-medium mb-3">
                Why Monitor Your Solar Panel Output?
                <p class="font-normal text-base max-w-[700px] mt-1">
                  Solar panels offer reliable power and can significantly reduce your energy bills. Monitoring the electricity your solar panels are producing
                  helps you:
                </p>
              </h1>

              <ol class="space-y-1 list-decimal list-inside">
                <li><b>Maximize Efficiency</b>: Knowing your output ensures that your panels are performing optimally.</li>
                <li><b>Track Savings:</b> It helps you calculate how much you're saving on electricity bills.</li>
                <li><b>Identify Issues Early:</b> Any drop in power generation could indicate problems like shading, dirt, or malfunctioning panels.</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h1 class="text-2xl font-medium mb-3">
                What You’ll Need to Calculate Your Solar Panel Output
                <p class="font-normal text-base max-w-[700px] mt-1">
                  To accurately calculate how much electricity your solar panels produce, you’ll need the following:
                </p>
              </h1>
              <ol class="space-y-1 list-disc list-inside">
                <li><b>Solar Panel Specifications:</b> Find out the wattage rating of your solar panels (typically 250W to 400W per panel).</li>
                <li><b>Inverter Efficiency:</b> Most inverters are about 90–95% efficient.</li>
                <li><b>Sunlight Hours in Nigeria:</b> Nigeria gets an average of 4–6 peak sunlight hours per day, depending on the region.</li>
                <li><b>Solar Power Output Formula:</b>Use this to estimate your daily production.</li>
              </ol>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h1 class="text-2xl font-medium mb-3">Step-by-Step Guide to Calculate Solar Panel Electricity Output</h1>
              <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-3">
                <li class="mt-2">
                  <b>Determine the Solar Panel Wattage</b>
                  <p>
                    Each solar panel has a specific wattage. For example, if your solar panel is rated at 300 watts (W), this is the maximum amount of
                    electricity it can produce under ideal conditions.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Identify Your Location’s Peak Sunlight Hours</b>
                  <p class="mt-2">
                    Nigeria has good solar potential, with an average of 4–6 peak sunlight hours per day. Peak sunlight hours refer to the time when the sun's
                    rays are strong enough to produce maximum energy. If you live in northern Nigeria, you might receive closer to 6 hours, while southern
                    regions may get around 4 hours.
                  </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Use the Formula: Solar Power Output (kWh) = Solar Panel Wattage × Peak Sunlight Hours × Number of Panels</b>
                  <p>Let’s break it down with an example:</p>
                  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 mt-2">
                    <li>You have a 300W solar panel.</li>
                    <li>You receive an average of 5 hours of peak sunlight daily.</li>
                    <li>You have 10 solar panels installed.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <div class="my-3 space-y-4">
                    <p>The daily electricity output is calculated as:</p>
                    <code class="bg-gray-500/10 px-5 py-2 rounded-lg block w-fit"> 300W × 5 hours × 10 panels = 15,000 watt-hours or 15 kWh/day </code>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <b>Account for Panels Efficiency</b>
                  <p>
                    No system is 100% efficient. Panels, for instance, typically operate at about 75% efficiency. To get a more accurate estimate of the amount
                    of usuable energy generated, multiply your result by the efficiency of your panels.
                  </p>
                  <div class="my-3 space-y-4">
                    <p>Using the previous example:</p>
                    <code class="bg-gray-500/10 px-5 py-2 rounded-lg block w-fit"> 15 kWh/day × 0.75 (75% efficiency) = 11.3 kWh/day </code>
                  </div>
                  So, with % 75% Panel efficiency, your panels produces 11.3 kWh of usable electricity daily, which can be stored in the battery for later or
                  used directly through the inverter.
                </li>
              </ol>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
